{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471642","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471642"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:49:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"380"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/380"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.71,0.08,0.01,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76750"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/380"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"380"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62243"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"696"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1579"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1643"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27717"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76750"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of colicky abdominal pain. He had been unwell with an upper respiratory tract infection a week ago which has now resolved. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The abdomen is soft and non-tender. There is no neck stiffness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe also complains of joint pain when the left knee is examined. A palpable purpuric rash is noted on his lower limbs. Urinalysis demonstrates blood ++ with no leucocytes or nitrites. Blood tests are unremarkable apart from a creatinine level of 125 \u03bcmol/L (53-115). An ultrasound of the abdomen demonstrates no acute pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial endocarditis","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","Haemolytic uraemic syndrome","Meningococcal septicaemia","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a classic presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E which presents with a characteristic palpable purpuric or petechial rash that is usually symmetrical and appears on gravity-dependent areas (e.g. buttocks and lower limbs in weight-bearing children). Other clinical features include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArthritis/arthralgia (50-75%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbdominal pain (50%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENephritis (25-50%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost cases of Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura are self-limiting and only require symptomatic management, but follow-up is required to identify significant renal involvement that may need intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is not consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E in which the child would be expected to be more unwell with systemic symptoms. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic uraemic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a purpuric rash but is usually associated with diarrhoea caused by infection with Shiga toxin\u2013producing strains of \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E (e.g. O157:H7 or O111:H8). The clinical presentation is not consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emeningococcal septicaemia\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003Cstrong\u003EPost-streptococcal glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E generally does not cause a purpuric rash.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most cases of Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura are self-limiting and do not need any formal intervention.","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura is an IgA-mediated small vessel vasculitis commonly seen in children."],"references":["Reamy BV, Williams PM, Lindsay TJ. Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura. Am Fam Physician. 2009 Oct 1;80(7):697-704. PMID: 19817340.","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne Clinical Practice Guidelines [Internet]. 2020 [updated 2021 Jan; cited 2020 Feb 15]. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/HenochSchonlein_Purpura/","eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (Vic): Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd; 2019.  Acute Infectious Diarrhoea [updated 2020 Apr; cited 2021 Feb 15]. Available from: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=acute-gastroenteritis\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic#toc_d1e1029","Hetland LE, Susrud KS, Lindahl KH, Bygum A. Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein Purpura: A Literature Review. Acta Derm Venereol. 2017 Nov 15;97(10):1160-1166. doi: 10.2340/00015555-2733. PMID: 28654132."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62243"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"380"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62243"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T20:10:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-24T20:28:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"380"}},"content":{"